Google 1-gram Data¶

The gift of data comes in many forms. Most of the time, it must be squeezed from stone, wrestled through API's and polished by hand. But not always. Sometimes it's just there, ready for the taking. The Google n-gram dataset the latter - a generous gift from Google to the world. Thanks Google!

I took the raw data removed all words with a word count under 10,000 and truncated the peroids 1800-1900, since the data from that peroid was just too noisy for my purposes. The result is the matrix X. Each X[:,i] here is a time series, corssponding to the word Word[i]

My first step is to do the following normalization to capture the relative popularity of each word as a proportion of all words written in a particular year.

In [66]:
X = readdlm("../data/T.dlm")
X = X./sum(X,2);
X = X./maximum(X,1)
X = X*5;

Words = readdlm("../data/Words.dlm");

Your first instinct, like mine, might be to try Principle Component Analysis on the data.

Some trends are clear, but the results aren't quite as distinct as I'd like them to be. The components bear a unfortunate resemble to fourier basis, with low frequencies at the top, and high frequencies at the bottom. Not surprising since we're dealing with time series data. These features aren't quite as informative as I'd like them to be.

Enter Non-Negative Matrix Factorization. Because the components can only interact constructively, I intuited it would get round the problem.

I played around with a few Julia Libraries, but to my dissapointment many of the algorithms do not converge properly. The best results were obtained by just coding the whole thing in proximal gradient by hand.

In [8]:
k = 8
n = size(X,1)
m = size(X,2)

# Inverse of the vector operator
function ivec(z)
    D = reshape(z[1:n*k], n,k)
    E = reshape(z[n*k + 1:end], m,k)
    return (D,E)
end

T = Tridiagonal(-ones(n-1), 2*ones(n), -ones(n-1))

# Gradient of objective function 
function f(z, arg = 0, α = 1., β = 0.1)
    (D,E) = ivec(z)
    R = X - D*E'
    fx = (vecnorm(R)^2)/2
    ∇gD = R*E
    ∇gE = R'*D
    return (fx, -[∇gD[:] - α*D[:] - β*(T*D)[:]; ∇gE[:] - α*E[:]])
end;

A note. Proximal gradient doesn't work well, if just applied in a vanilla sense. But adding momentum changes the game completely. This phenomena is well documented in the deep learning literature, see here, for example.

In [9]:
prox = (x) -> [max(0, x[1:n*k]); max(0,x[n*k+1:end])]

x = 2*randn((n+m)*k)
y = zeros((n+m)*k)
t = 0.0001;
CONV = []

for i = 1:200*1
    (fy, ∇fy) = f(y)
    x = prox(x - t*∇fy)
    y = 0.95*y + x
    push!(CONV, fy)
end

How well does the model fit the data? Much better than hoped.

As it turns out, there are very striking regularities in the way words come in and out of being. With a few hundred exceptions to the rule, the model works beautifully.
